   Also it triggered me to implement another change - those tokens can be now removed by admin "purge-token" option as well as they will automatically purge themselves when Oauth metadata indicate that groups/permissions of the user changed in LDAP (ASF Oauth already provides that information) - which adds additional memory savings and database savings. Previously, those tokens would have been rejected if auth interface would reject the token - now (if enabled) the tokens will be "out of abundance of caution" immediately removed when we see any "permission/group change" for the user when it tries to login with token that was generated with previous set of permissions.


