> On Jul 13, 2026, at 6:12 AM, Bowen, Rich <rbowen@apache.org> wrote:
>=20
>=20
>=20
>> On Jul 13, 2026, at 8:56=E2=80=AFAM, Dave Fisher <wave@apache.org> =
wrote:
>>=20
>> HI Rich,
>>=20
>> This is cool. Some thoughts.
>>=20
>> 1) On the Community Growth Tab new PMCs dominate the list. Would it =
make sense to have two lists?
>=20
> I assume you mean adding PMC growth and committer growth separately? =
Yeah, that would probably make more sense. But getting the new committer =
data has always been a bit tricksy, since the only data that I can =
reliably find is icla dates, which is *often* the same thing, but not =
always. Is that data that I can get via an API call somewhere that I =
don=E2=80=99t know about?

Yes, it is a tricky bit of code in the reporter. There is an ldap pubsub =
feed that needs to be processed. You have to notice the change in the =
PMC=E2=80=99s committer list. You could ask Infra about how to use that =
and what credentials you would need.

> Related to that, I run reports for a couple of dozen projects that I =
care about $WorkHat, which calculates who is likely to be the *next* =
committer, if the project is paying attention. I=E2=80=99d like to =
provide that report, somehow, to PMCs, but it=E2=80=99s potentially =
sensitive, in much the say way that new committer votes can be =
sensitive. I=E2=80=99d need to figure out how to auth that to only =
members of those PMCs. That=E2=80=99s on my To Do list.

You can send from an @apache.org address to private@pmc. Or you can make =
your site an asfquart app, use MFA, and you will get project/pmc auth as =
part of the framework. You could look into the recent CAP work by Infra =
as an example.

>=20
>>=20
>> 2) Tooling is working on a catalog feature for the ATR Beta. In a few =
months we can likely hook you up with better data. I=E2=80=99ll note =
that if you are using the zzz/find file then you are using a method that =
mostly counts release artifacts where many PMC=E2=80=99s projects like =
Airflow Providers and OpenOffice release dozens or hundreds of artifacts =
in a single release. It might be interesting to count only source and =
binary convenience separately.
>=20
> I went pawing through the complete svn log for dist.apache.org (`svn =
log https://dist.apache.org/repos/dist/release/` =
<https://dist.apache.org/repos/dist/release/%60>) this weekend, and I =
think that might be another way to get this data, but having a simpler =
source of that info available via an API call would be fantastic.

We=E2=80=99ve done that too, it=E2=80=99s hit or miss. For ATR we =
started watching changes to pick up non-ATR releases, changes to KEYS =
